ial; font-size:12pt">How does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">How reliable is the Governme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nt’s forecast for growth in demand for the strategic road network?  How should the Government deal with uncertainty in its forecast?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">How can we improve the reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network?  What impact will new technolog</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y have?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">What mechanisms are there for Government to increase investment in strategic roads and attract new investors?  Are there good examples from other countries that could be applied in the UK?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">How should the Highways Agency be reformed to make it the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ‘world’s leading highway operator’?  What roles should Government and the private sector play to ensure better management of the strategic road network?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This submission addresses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">draws</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on Oxfordshire County Council’s role as the Local Transport Authori</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ty, its involvement with the Oxfordshire Local Enterprise Partnership (to which it provides technical and administrative support), its role in chairing the Local Transport Board and its contribution to the development of the Oxfordshire City-Deal proposal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(which in turn will inform the development of the Strategic Economic Plan for Oxfordshire).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Its central location and entrepreneurial culture, feeding of the innovation that comes from being the seat of two world class universities, means that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Oxford is a global brand that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is an attractive location for economic growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Its transport system has to provide effective and efficient movement around Oxfordshire, as well as providing strong, reliable connections with the rest of the UK and its intern</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ational gateways (such as London Heathrow and London St Pancras).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The A34 Trunk Road is a critical part of the transport system in Oxfordshire.  It’s management and future development is inextricably intertwined with the wider transport system in Oxfordsh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ire – a transport system that is one of three building blocks upon </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the success of the Oxfordshire economy is critically dependent (the others being skills and housing).  The M40 corridor similarly plays a key role in the Oxfordshire transport system,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> providing links with central London </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with the West Midlands and beyond.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Oxfordshire’s work on its City-Deal proposal has reinforce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the need to consider and plan the development of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">transport networks as a single transport system.  To plan the deve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lopment of individual networks in isolation of one another misses the singularly important consideration that customers – the consumers of transport – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are not constrained in their choice of travel to only one mode of travel: indeed an individual can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">make d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ifferent choices </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">if </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">circumstances change.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In this context the Government has a key role to play by setting out </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a strategic vision </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for the development of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">networks on a co-ordinated basis.  It would be important for such a vision to be ‘light-touch’ s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o as to avoid fettering the ability of network operators or service providers to implement market-driven solutions.  However, the importance of setting a national vision cannot be over-emphasised.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Within Oxfordshire the rail network is benefiting from sig</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nificant public sector investment.  That investment, which will remove bottlenecks and provide capacity for further expansion, is already demonstrating tangible benefits.  Public sector investment to increase the gauge along the rail corridor has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">led to an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> increase in rail’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">share of container movements from the South Coast to the West Midlands.  That in turn </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will reduce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">long distance lorry movements along the A34. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is immediately apparent that the longer term planning of the A34 as part of the S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">trategi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c Road Network </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">take place within a policy framework that considers the inter-relationship between individual networks, and more importantly the implication of investment in one network on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">operation of others.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The legislative framework that would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">enable a ‘light-touch’ vision for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">co-ordinated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">development of England’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">strategic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">transport networks already exists in the form of the opportunity to publish a National Policy Statement for Strategic Networks (under the Planning Act 200</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">).  In seeking </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to restructure the Highways Agency it is imperative that the Government fills this policy v</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">acuum as a matter of priority.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">developing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the National Policy Statement, the Government might wish to draw on the experience of the devolved administrations in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scotland and Wales in developing their National Infrastructure Plans.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The development of the National Policy Statement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provide the opportunity to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">redefine purpose and function of the Strategic Road Network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and in turn the role of the Highways Agency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  There is an assumption inherent within the current approach of the Highways Agency that long-distance ‘strategic’ traffic should be prioritised over short-distance movements: the inference being that the latter has a lower comparative value.  Such an as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sumption is out dated and needs to be challenged.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Oxfordshire economy is the home of ‘Big Science’ within the UK.  It has research and development facilities that are truly world-class and which attract investment from across the global economy.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A34 corridor in Oxfordshire forms a key part of the transport system that connects the centres of innovation in Oxfordshire with those research facilities.  Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e ability of the A34 to accommodate local movements therefore has a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">high strategic value </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in econo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mic terms </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ensuring that the UK remains globally competitive for key sectors of the Government’s business strategy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In comparison, longer-distance movements on the A34 in Oxfordshire may have lesser strategic value</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Such arguments become all the more</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> pertinent if investment in other networks provides a viable and attractive alternative.  By way of example, the Government’s investment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the rail network </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is providing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">longer-distance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">freight </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">movements with a via</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ble alternative to using the A34.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Oxfords</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hire County Council accepts that there will always be a need to balance competing demands on transport infrastructure that has a finite capacity.  However, as Oxfordshire’s example illustrates, if the objective is to maximise the benefit of overall public </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sector investment to the UK economy, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">then it is important that investment decisions are take on a co-ordinated basis within an overall policy framework that sets out a vision for an integrated transport system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Setting out how national investment in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">transport infrastructure supports overall UK competitiveness will require Government to identify clear priorities.  Oxfordshire County Council argues that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">prioritising </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">investment in support of the UK global brands – such as Oxford, London, Cambridge – is u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ltimately to the benefit of the UK as a whole and should therefore be given a high priority nationally.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Oxfordshire experience also illustrates the importance of ensuring that whilst there is a need for a National Policy Statement, it is critical that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> this is ‘light-touch’.  The role of individual networks in support of the local economy will be hugely dependent upon local circumstances.  To try and capture th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">within a single national policy document is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">impractical.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At present the Highways Agency pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ocesses are overly prescriptive and lack the flexibility that is required to deal with the real world.  By way of example, the A34 in Oxfordshire forms part of a wider Route Based Strategy that stretches from the South Coast to the Midlands.  The Highways </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Agency’s approach will see its initial base-line study completed by spring 2014 and a strategy for the corridor developed by spring 2015.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In stark contrast, Oxfordshire County Council has completed a base-line study within 3 months and is working through </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the partnership established as part of its work on the City-Deal to identify a preferred strategy for the A34 corridor by spring 2014.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the time it will take the Highways Agency to complete its base-line work local partners will have developed their Cit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y-Deal, used that to develop the Oxfordshire Strategic Economic Plan, put in place a European Investment Strategy and have prepared proposals for submission to the Local Growth Fund.  In addition, in the time it will take the Highways Agency to complete it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s Route Based Strategy, local partners will have delivered (in partnership with the Agency) improvements to three key junctions along the A34 corridor in Oxfordshire.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">What is pertinent is that the pace at which the County Council and its local partners ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e working is a consequence of Government encouragement for them to be more ambitious and accelerate the delivery of economic growth.  The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">contrast with Highways Agency’s processes (which are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> set by the same Government) is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> marked and suggests that more coul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d, and should, be done to simplify the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ir </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">processes and procedures.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In this context i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t is interesting to note that Oxfordshire’s attempt to seek a relaxation in those processes as part of its City-Deal was rejected very early on in the process.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> development of a ‘light-touch’ framework – in the form of the National Policy Statement – will ensure that policy linkages across transport modes is strengthened, there is also a need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for national policy to take </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">into account other policy initiatives.  Thi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s is particularly true where those initiatives are likely to have a significant impact on travel choices and travel demand in the future.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">By way of example, Oxfordshire County Council (like all County Councils) has let a contract that will see a step chan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ge in broadband coverage across the County.  With Government policy emphasising the importance of investment in digital infrastructure, the implications of this investment on travel has yet to be reflected within Government thinking on future transport req</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uirements.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is truism that transport is a derived demand.  It is therefore essential that in considering future transport requirements – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as set out in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">traffic forecasts – the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">needs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to review the tools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that are available to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">assist decision mak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The consumer market for trans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">port services is not homogenous.  Our use of transport varies according to the stage at which we are in our life, and our local circumstances.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is therefore important to develop a better understanding of both existin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g and future consumer needs, including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the implication of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">socio-economic and demographic changes.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The needs and expectations of Oxfordshire’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> growing population of over 85-year olds will be different from those of its student population, or its workforce, or indeed the international placements in our research facilities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In seeking to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">understand the needs and aspirations of the various market </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">segments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it is important to recognise that businesses (both existing and potential inward investors) are as much a consumer as the individual.  It is an approach that Oxfordshire County Council is looking to apply as it begins to update its Local Transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Plan.  Such an approach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is likely to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mean that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">forecasting and ap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">praisal tools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">currently in operation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">need to be updated.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Viewing the consumer market on a segmented basis </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is likely to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">assist in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shaping the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">performance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">framework for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a restructured Hig</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hways Agency.  This will be particularly important i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f we are to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">avoid creating incentives for a new Agency that run counter to the objectives </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">set out for a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">co-ordinated transport system </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">National Policy Statement.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In this context there is a need to define the future role of the Highways Agency.  At the moment the Agency is part operator, part commissioner, part policy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">developer.  This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">confusion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">needs to be resolved.  If the Strategic Road Network is to be operated u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sing a model similar to that used for regulated utilities then the outcome/output </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sought needs to be appropriately defined. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst the statutory process for developing a National Policy Statement includes provision for local input, the development of out</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">come/output measures needs to take into account the local circumstances.  Oxfordshire County Council consider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that the Local Transport Board could be an appropriate forum in which performance measures for the Strategic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Road Network might be discussed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e Local Transport Board </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">already exists as a public/private sector partnership, one that works closely with the Local Enterprise Partnership to advise Government on local transport priorities.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In Oxfordshire membership of the Local Transport Board is exten</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ded to include representatives of the Highways Agency and public transport operators.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Its approach to prioritisation is founded in the need to align the allocation of available funds to support the delivery of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">planned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">growth.  Extending its scope to adv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ise on the identification of outcome/output measures for the Strategic Road Network would be consistent with the Government’s commitment to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">localism.  Setting those measures within the context of a ‘light-touch’ vision set out nationally would ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any such measure also takes into UK strategic priorities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If the overarching objective is to ensure greater value for money and more effective co-ordination of investment (to maximise the benefit to the UK economy), there is a need to provide a greater de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gree of certainty as to the public sector funding envelope.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A ten-year indicative funding envelope would bring two potential benefits.  Firstly it would enable the public sector to commission scheme development work with greater certainty.  Business cas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e development could be timed to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">align with the availability of f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">unding, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reducing the risk to local authorities of committing funding to such work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  With funding pressures on local government continuing, reducing the risk of abortive work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> offers the prospec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t of efficiency savings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The second potential benefit of greater certainty of the public sector funding is that it would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">better define the extent to which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">alternative funding mechanisms – including but not limited to private sector funding – might extend </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the total funding available.  S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">et </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">within the framework of a ‘light-touch’ National Policy Statement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this would provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">potential </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">investors with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">greater clarity as to the likely level of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">risk associated with a potential investment.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Oxfordshire County Coun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cil supports the proposition that the application of technology to manage the Strategic Road Network will be an important consideration for the Highways Agency.  As part of its City-Deal proposal Oxfordshire is seeking support for the extension of ‘active </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">traffic management’ principles to the A34 corridor.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is looking to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">commit to ensuring that there are no legislative or regulatory barriers to allowing such principles to be used where they are justified.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition, Oxfordshire </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">County Council is keen to ensure that information relating to the performance of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the Strategic Road Network is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">made available on an ‘open source’ basis so that it could be included within the warehouse of data relating to the operation of the transport net</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">works.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Oxfordshire’s ambition to facilitate a customer orientated, co-ordinated transport system is set out in its proposal for the Oxford Science Transit.  Such a system can only be developed in partnership with the private sector and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">need to be sup</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ported by investment in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">co-ordinating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">travel </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">information systems </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that place the customer at the heart of travel choices</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Experience </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">suggests </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the market is well placed to develop innovative customer orientated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">systems and a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pps</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that provide the customer with travel choice information.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Transport network operators in both the public and private sectors have a role to play in enabling the development of such solutions by making information on the operation of their networks availa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ble on an open source basis.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A commitment should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be placed upon the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Highways Agency </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to make its operational information available on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">such a basis.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Oxfordshire County Council would be willing to expand upon any of the points made in this submiss</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ion if that assists the Select Committee in their enquiry.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><spa